Technically, you're wrong too, on pretty much all accounts. Hyenas aren't felids, since that would imply that they're practically as closely related to house cats as something like a lynx or a cougar or even a tiger, but that's not the case. Hyenas are hyaenids, since that's the family they come from. Hyaenids and felids both fall under feliformia, though, so they're related under that banner but like you said, with genetics we can tell how things are literally related, even in a which-species-is-more-closely-related-to-which sense.

You also also borked it with caniformia. Raccoons are Procyonids, and red pandas are Ailurids, both of which are Musteloids which does fall under caniformia but the only one you named that is actually a canid is the Raccoon-Dog. Canid is the family where your more traditional doggos and foxes are. Pretty much meaning that raccoons are more closely related to red pandas or skunks than they are related to raccoon-dogs, and raccoon dogs are more closely related to house dogs than they're related to weasels, yet all of these fall under caniformia.
